objects.description:
Adversaries may send phishing messages to gain access to victim systems. All forms of phishing are electronically delivered social engineering. Phishing can be targeted, known as spearphishing. In spearphishing, a specific individual, company, or industry will be targeted by the adversary. More generally, adversaries can conduct non-targeted phishing, such as in mass malware spam campaigns.

Adversaries may send victims emails containing malicious attachments or links, typically to execute malicious code on victim systems. Phishing may also be conducted via third-party services, like social media platforms. Phishing may also involve social engineering techniques, such as posing as a trusted source, as well as evasive techniques such as removing or manipulating emails or metadata/headers from compromised accounts being abused to send messages (e.g., Email Hiding Rules). Another way to accomplish this is by forging or spoofing the identity of the sender which can be used to fool both the human recipient as well as automated security tools.

Victims may also receive phishing messages that instruct them to call a phone number where they are directed to visit a malicious URL, download malware, or install adversary-accessible remote management tools onto their computer (i.e., User Execution).

objects.name: Phishing
objects.x_mitre_detection:
Network intrusion detection systems and email gateways can be used to detect phishing with malicious attachments in transit. Detonation chambers may also be used to identify malicious attachments. Solutions can be signature and behavior based, but adversaries may construct attachments in a way to avoid these systems.

Filtering based on DKIM+SPF or header analysis can help detect when the email sender is spoofed.(Citation: Microsoft Anti Spoofing)(Citation: ACSC Email Spoofing)

URL inspection within email (including expanding shortened links) can help detect links leading to known malicious sites. Detonation chambers can be used to detect these links and either automatically go to these sites to determine if they're potentially malicious, or wait and capture the content if a user visits the link.

Because most common third-party services used for phishing via service leverage TLS encryption, SSL/TLS inspection is generally required to detect the initial communication/delivery. With SSL/TLS inspection intrusion detection signatures or other security gateway appliances may be able to detect malware.

Anti-virus can potentially detect malicious documents and files that are downloaded on the user's computer. Many possible detections of follow-on behavior may take place once [User Execution](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1204) occurs.

objects.description: Adversaries may shutdown/reboot systems to interrupt access to, or aid in the destruction of, those systems. Operating systems may contain commands to initiate a shutdown/reboot of a machine or network device. In some cases, these commands may also be used to initiate a shutdown/reboot of a remote computer or network device via [Network Device CLI](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/008) (e.g. reload).(Citation: Microsoft Shutdown Oct 2017)(Citation: alert_TA18_106A) Shutting down or rebooting systems may disrupt access to computer resources for legitimate users while also impeding incident response/recovery. Adversaries may attempt to shutdown/reboot a system after impacting it in other ways, such as [Disk Structure Wipe](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1561/002) or [Inhibit System Recovery](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1490), to hasten the intended effects on system availability.(Citation: Talos Nyetya June 2017)(Citation: Talos Olympic Destroyer 2018)

objects.name: System Shutdown/Reboot
objects.x_mitre_detection: Use process monitoring to monitor the execution and command line parameters of binaries involved in shutting down or rebooting systems. Windows event logs may also designate activity associated with a shutdown/reboot, ex. Event ID 1074 and 6006. Unexpected or unauthorized commands from network cli on network devices may also be associated with shutdown/reboot, e.g. the reload command.

objects.description:
Adversaries may transfer tools or other files between systems in a compromised environment. Once brought into the victim environment (i.e., [Ingress Tool Transfer](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1105)) files may then be copied from one system to another to stage adversary tools or other files over the course of an operation.

Adversaries may copy files between internal victim systems to support lateral movement using inherent file sharing protocols such as file sharing over [SMB/Windows Admin Shares](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1021/002) to connected network shares or with authenticated connections via [Remote Desktop Protocol](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1021/001).(Citation: Unit42 LockerGoga 2019)

Files can also be transferred using native or otherwise present tools on the victim system, such as scp, rsync, curl, sftp, and [ftp](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0095). In some cases, adversaries may be able to leverage [Web Service](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1102)s such as Dropbox or OneDrive to copy files from one machine to another via shared, automatically synced folders.(Citation: Dropbox Malware Sync)

objects.name: Lateral Tool Transfer
objects.x_mitre_detection: Monitor for file creation and files transferred within a network using protocols such as SMB or FTP. Unusual processes with internal network connections creating files on-system may be suspicious. Consider monitoring for abnormal usage of utilities and command-line arguments that may be used in support of remote transfer of files. Considering monitoring for alike file hashes or characteristics (ex: filename) that are created on multiple hosts.

objects.description: Adversaries may delete or remove built-in data and turn off services designed to aid in the recovery of a corrupted system to prevent recovery.(Citation: Talos Olympic Destroyer 2018)(Citation: FireEye WannaCry 2017) This may deny access to available backups and recovery options. Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may disable or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of [Data Destruction](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1485) and [Data Encrypted for Impact](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1486).(Citation: Talos Olympic Destroyer 2018)(Citation: FireEye WannaCry 2017) Furthermore, adversaries may disable recovery notifications, then corrupt backups.(Citation: disable_notif_synology_ransom) A number of native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features: * vssadmin.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system - vssadmin.exe delete shadows /all /quiet * [Windows Management Instrumentation](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1047) can be used to delete volume shadow copies - wmic shadowcopy delete * wbadmin.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog - wbadmin.exe delete catalog -quiet * bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data - bcdedit.exe /set {default} bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set {default} recoveryenabled no * REAgentC.exe can be used to disable Windows Recovery Environment (WinRE) repair/recovery options of an infected system On network devices, adversaries may leverage [Disk Wipe](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1561) to delete backup firmware images and reformat the file system, then [System Shutdown/Reboot](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1529) to reload the device. Together this activity may leave network devices completely inoperable and inhibit recovery operations. Adversaries may also delete online backups that are connected to their network whether via network storage media or through folders that sync to cloud services.(Citation: ZDNet Ransomware Backups 2020) In cloud environments, adversaries may disable versioning and backup policies and delete snapshots, machine images, and prior versions of objects designed to be used in disaster recovery scenarios.(Citation: Dark Reading Code Spaces Cyber Attack)(Citation: Rhino Security Labs AWS S3 Ransomware)

objects.name: Inhibit System Recovery
x_mitre_data_sources: Windows Registry: Windows Registry Key Modification
objects.x_mitre_detection: Use process monitoring to monitor the execution and command line parameters of binaries involved in inhibiting system recovery, such as vssadmin, wbadmin, bcdedit and REAgentC. The Windows event logs, ex. Event ID 524 indicating a system catalog was deleted, may contain entries associated with suspicious activity. Monitor the status of services involved in system recovery. Monitor the registry for changes associated with system recovery features (ex: the creation of HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Policies\Microsoft\PreviousVersions\DisableLocalPage). For network infrastructure devices, collect AAA logging to monitor for `erase`, `format`, and `reload` commands being run in succession.

objects.description: Adversaries may destroy data and files on specific systems or in large numbers on a network to interrupt availability to systems, services, and network resources. Data destruction is likely to render stored data irrecoverable by forensic techniques through overwriting files or data on local and remote drives.(Citation: Symantec Shamoon 2012)(Citation: FireEye Shamoon Nov 2016)(Citation: Palo Alto Shamoon Nov 2016)(Citation: Kaspersky StoneDrill 2017)(Citation: Unit 42 Shamoon3 2018)(Citation: Talos Olympic Destroyer 2018) Common operating system file deletion commands such as del and rm often only remove pointers to files without wiping the contents of the files themselves, making the files recoverable by proper forensic methodology. This behavior is distinct from [Disk Content Wipe](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1561/001) and [Disk Structure Wipe](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1561/002) because individual files are destroyed rather than sections of a storage disk or the disk's logical structure. Adversaries may attempt to overwrite files and directories with randomly generated data to make it irrecoverable.(Citation: Kaspersky StoneDrill 2017)(Citation: Unit 42 Shamoon3 2018) In some cases politically oriented image files have been used to overwrite data.(Citation: FireEye Shamoon Nov 2016)(Citation: Palo Alto Shamoon Nov 2016)(Citation: Kaspersky StoneDrill 2017) To maximize impact on the target organization in operations where network-wide availability interruption is the goal, malware designed for destroying data may have worm-like features to propagate across a network by leveraging additional techniques like [Valid Accounts](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1078), [OS Credential Dumping](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1003), and [SMB/Windows Admin Shares](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1021/002).(Citation: Symantec Shamoon 2012)(Citation: FireEye Shamoon Nov 2016)(Citation: Palo Alto Shamoon Nov 2016)(Citation: Kaspersky StoneDrill 2017)(Citation: Talos Olympic Destroyer 2018). In cloud environments, adversaries may leverage access to delete cloud storage, cloud storage accounts, machine images, and other infrastructure crucial to operations to damage an organization or their customers.(Citation: Data Destruction - Threat Post)(Citation: DOJ - Cisco Insider)

objects.name: Data Destruction
objects.x_mitre_detection: Use process monitoring to monitor the execution and command-line parameters of binaries that could be involved in data destruction activity, such as [SDelete](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0195). Monitor for the creation of suspicious files as well as high unusual file modification activity. In particular, look for large quantities of file modifications in user directories and under C:\Windows\System32\. In cloud environments, the occurrence of anomalous high-volume deletion events, such as the DeleteDBCluster and DeleteGlobalCluster events in AWS, or a high quantity of data deletion events, such as DeleteBucket, within a short period of time may indicate suspicious activity.

objects.description:
Adversaries may attempt to access cached domain credentials used to allow authentication to occur in the event a domain controller is unavailable.(Citation: Microsoft - Cached Creds)

On Windows Vista and newer, the hash format is DCC2 (Domain Cached Credentials version 2) hash, also known as MS-Cache v2 hash.(Citation: PassLib mscache) The number of default cached credentials varies and can be altered per system. This hash does not allow pass-the-hash style attacks, and instead requires [Password Cracking](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1110/002) to recover the plaintext password.(Citation: ired mscache)

With SYSTEM access, the tools/utilities such as [Mimikatz](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0002), [Reg](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0075), and secretsdump.py can be used to extract the cached credentials.

Note: Cached credentials for Windows Vista are derived using PBKDF2.(Citation: PassLib mscache)

objects.name: OS Credential Dumping: Cached Domain Credentials
objects.x_mitre_detection:
Monitor processes and command-line arguments for program execution that may be indicative of credential dumping. Remote access tools may contain built-in features or incorporate existing tools like Mimikatz. PowerShell scripts also exist that contain credential dumping functionality, such as PowerSploit's Invoke-Mimikatz module,(Citation: Powersploit) which may require additional logging features to be configured in the operating system to collect necessary information for analysis.

Detection of compromised [Valid Accounts](https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1078) in-use by adversaries may help as well.

objects.description:
Sandworm is a well known Russian-speaking threat actor responsible for destabilization campaigns by doing sabotage and leaking operations against occidental interests. This intrusion set has been attributed by several intelligence agencies to Russia's **[General Staff Main Intelligence Directorate (GRU)](/intelligence/objects/threat-actor--ca2f2a66-74c5-4c68-80a3-ec43478d8f50) Main Center for Special Technologies (GTsST) military unit 74455**. 

According to open sources, **Sandworm has been active since at least 2008 when they had attempted Distributed Denial of Service attacks (DDoS)** by using the first version of the [BackEnergy malware](/intelligence/objects/malware--52de4136-9d17-453a-aba5-0b6c681a671d) during the Russo-Georgian war. Following this first appearance on the international scene, Sandworm made the headlines in several international crises implicating Russia such as in Ukraine, following the Euromaidan crisis (2013) by doing several **sabotage campaigns against the Ukrainian government, media, transports and energy sector**. 

During the 2014-2022 cold confratation between Russian and Ukraine, Sandworm was also responsible for the creation of the [NotPetya worm](/intelligence/objects/malware--30a3a093-00e5-438f-a7ca-aa5d8ef92e03) that has been spread in hundreds of networks connected to Ukrainian entities. NotPetya, by mimicking ransomware, had sabotage capabilities **causing several billion dollars of damage for the infected companies**.

Sandworm is known to have been implicated in other crises such as the 2018 Winter Olympics destabilization attempt with the infamous [Olympic Destroyer](/intelligence/objects/malware--2fa4b91a-7684-494d-a0f6-71215867833e) malware or the Skripal case, by trying to **compromise physically the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons** and several laboratories working on this case (2018) via spear phishing campaigns. 

One of the most famous destabilization attempts done by the Sandworm intrusion set is the **French Macron Leaks (2017)** when the operators compromised several mailboxes of Macron staff members to leak their content to Wikileaks and on the /pol/ board of the (now defunct) 4Chan forum. This operation was a small part of a much wider spear phishing campaign targeting many sectors and individuals, related by Google TAG in 2020.

Even though Sandworm closely works with another GRU-linked intrusion set dubbed as [APT28](/intelligence/objects/intrusion-set--40479e35-a7ca-4c05-998d-2cf21ab751cc), their operators employ different TTPs. **Sandworm is more flexible and seems dedicated to special destabilization operations involving a smaller footprint in the targeted entities**. 

**Sandworm is largely active since the beginning of the Russia-Ukraine war**, conducting campaigns for **intelligence collection**, **multiple destructive network attacks**, contributing to **information operations**, and even, according to Google, using hack-for-hire services to secure initial access to some targets. 
Sandworn levareged multiple **straightforward** and **ready-to-use wipers** (HermeticWiper, AcidRain, Industroyer2, ZeroWipe, SwiftSlicer...) looking to [contribute](https://blog.sekoia.io/one-year-after-the-cyber-implications-of-the-russo-ukrainian-war/) to Russian intelligence to work faster, looking for more immediate effects  rather than complex and long-term planned destructive worms. 

# TTPs

One of the main characteristics of this intrusion set is to **use mostly open source tools for initial access ([Empire](/intelligence/objects/malware--43650dc8-980b-4b5f-9646-476cccbae2f7), [Meterpreter](/intelligence/objects/tool--38d6ece7-4244-4dcd-a4fe-5c150c561b8b), remote administration tools)** and **tailored and destructive malware to achieve their operations** such as [Industroyer](/intelligence/objects/malware--b0fab28c-b86a-4140-946e-0bd2a26e191c), [BadRabbit](/intelligence/objects/malware--461ca82d-640f-43b5-911a-97763e400899), NotPetya or even Olympic Destroyer. Sandworm intrusion set proven to master all of intrusion vectors from spear phishing to watering holes, frontal compromise and supply chain attacks. Moreover, they showed **their ability to develop their own modular implants for SOHO routers such as [VPN Filter](/intelligence/objects/malware--d9e9a85d-dbd9-471c-bb39-c70d122ada7f) and [Cyclops Blink](/intelligence/objects/malware--a76416d2-0551-4843-8c9f-fdf930a168e9) to constitute their own botnet**. 

Regarding its infrastructure, Sandworm is using compromised websites and VPS servers. **The use of domain names by this intrusion set is very rare** and they rely mostly on IPv4 addresses in their malware configuration. Historically, they also set up TOR relays on their C2s. **This use of TOR relays can be related to an attempt to prevent SIGINT interception**.

Since 2018, the Sandworm intrusion set operators have been subject to different lawsuits and public shaming from occidental authorities. In 2018, four sandworm operators were caught by the General Intelligence and Security Service of the Netherlands (AIVD) during a close access operation against the OPCW network. Following this raid, the identities of the GRU members and their attack methods were disclosed to the public.

In October 2020, the US Department of Justice indicted six other operators working for the Sandworm instruction set. These GRU Unit 74455 officers were indicted for several cyber operations such as NotPetya attack, the Macron Leaks, Olympic Destroyer or the operation against the OPCW network. Some of these attacks were conducted with the assistance of GRU Unit 26165, which is also dubbed as APT28. 

### 2022-2023 Russia-Ukraine war activity

Despite the public shaming and the indictments, and after a quiet period in 2021, Sandworm came back to the stage with the beginning of the Russo-Ukrainian War, with multiple compromise and sabotage operations targeting Ukrainian and occidental entities (mainly coutries supporting Kiev)

Sandworm was observed by many cybersecurity vendors using several kind of wipers impacting Ukraine entities.
* [Acid Rain wiper](/intelligence/objects/malware--0a2df090-4065-4a9d-a21e-84b6f0e9694d), used in the VIA-SAT operation impacting satellite communication
* [CaddyWiper](/intelligence/objects/malware--ab89b963-512f-41ca-be8b-3f77c0de651b) (used by APT28 as well), alongside Ar[guepatch d](/intelligence/objects/malware--b2016a76-1eaa-4367-808a-7cc2f4eb36cd)ropper
* [Prestige Ransomware](/intelligence/objects/malware--7114b03e-ec78-4820-9009-7af893930a6c), used as a wiper to target transportation and logistics industries in Ukraine and Poland.
* [AWFULSHRED](/intelligence/objects/malware--52eaa90b-aa36-4e09-bd6c-216d9b3ed463), used in a desctrutive operation impactive the Ukrainian Press Agency.
* [ZeroWipe](/intelligence/objects/malware--30b81fbb-0109-4439-93e8-1d6d8a4dd502), used in a destructive operation impactive the Ukrainian Press Agency.
* [SwiftSlicer](/intelligence/objects/malware--a04a6636-61b7-4390-8671-108937b74b8e)

objects.description:
[APT3](https://attack.mitre.org/groups/G0022) is an intrusion set that has been active from at least 2009 to 2019 and which is attributed by researchers to **[Chinas Ministry of State Security](https://www.recordedfuture.com/chinese-mss-behind-apt3)** and the company **Boyusec.**

It ran several campaigns that have succeeded. The first campaigns known in open source took place in 2014 with the **Operation Clandestine Fox** that infected users through a 0 day vulnerability affecting Internet Explorer. APT3 used spear phishing emails with malicious links leading to webpages exploiting this vulnerability.. This campaign was followed by **Operation Double Tap** in November 2014 which targeted multiple organizations also with spear phishing leading to a 0day exploitation. Then came **Operation Clandestine Wolf** in 2015 where the group exploited a zero-day vulnerability affecting Adobe flash, targeting Hong Kong and possibly other states. CrowdStrike reports showed that the group was active until 2019 during campaigns with other hacker groups such as Turbine Panda to steal intellectual property from 2010 to 2019 in aerospace companies in order to build Chinese C919 airplanes.

**Reported victimology**

This group has targeted the US, Europe, Asia (South Korea, India and Vietnam) and Hong Kong since 2015.
Its targeted organizations are in different sectors such as aerospace and defense, energy, high technology, construction and engineering, telecommunications and transportation.

**TTPs**

APT3 used mainly **spear phishing campaigns** with malicious links leading to zero-day vulnerabilities affecting web browsers (such as Internet Explorer) and their plugins (Adobe Flash Player). APT3 was known to be very agile and use their own implants in the victim network such as Pirpi, their validator which was deployed following a successful exploitation and UPS their persistence backdoor, installed on specific assets inside the network.

**Toolset**

APT3 used its own implants inside the compromised networks, known as Pirpi and UPS.
According to [Symantec](https://symantec-enterprise-blogs.security.com/blogs/threat-intelligence/buckeye-windows-zero-day-exploit), APT3 used Equation Group Tools a year before the Shadow Brokers Leak in 2017. However, it is likely possible that Equation Group used APT3 previous accesses via SIGINT interception on Filensfer or Pirpi backdoor to piggyback APT3.  . 
The malwares used by APT3 were Pirpi Backdoor (also known as CookieCutter and [Shotput](https://app.sekoia.io/intelligence/objects/malware--6f2b63e9-2e1b-4407-86bd-1f7519a081e0)), UPSOSInfo, [RemoteCMD](https://app.sekoia.io/intelligence/objects/malware--09970f39-81e8-4dbb-a7fb-53a39135449c), and possibly [PlugX](https://app.sekoia.io/intelligence/objects/malware--1bd27a17-2c45-4864-bc7c-b2c77ddd17ac) (aka. Sogu).

objects.description:
**APT28** is a Russia-nexus intrusion set attributed by Western intelligence services to [Russia's General Staff Main Intelligence Directorate (GRU)](/intelligence/objects/threat-actor--ca2f2a66-74c5-4c68-80a3-ec43478d8f50**) 85th Main Special Service Center** (GTsSS) Military **Unit 26165**. This intrusion set, which started its operations in 2004 against occidental Military networks, is especially known for its hybrid operations on the sidelines of armed conflict and diplomatic crises related to Russia. 

It was in 2014 with a report called "Operation Pawn Storm" released by Trend Micro that the  public became aware of this intrusion set. Since then, APT28 has made the headlines during several espionage, destabilization and sabotage operations.

Its intrusion techniques are most often singular, such as spear phishing using a malicious attachment or leading to a watering hole, credentials theft by using malicious emails associated with domain typo-squatting or dns hijacking. APT28 is also known for achieving VPN / RDP frontal compromises and IOT compromises in order to get a foothold in the targeted networks. This intrusion set is also suspected to have achieved at least one attack by a supply chain in central Asia.

The APT28 intrusion set was designated historically by its tools, that are for a large part developed internally, such as the malicious code X-TUNNEL, the X-AGENT backdoor, the UEFI rootkit dubbed [LoJax](/intelligence/objects/malware--293bc1ee-5d2e-4d07-8e78-e2c31df62cf9)", or the CORESHELL validator. Using these tools mostly during its operations, APT28 seems to have left them for the use of open source offensive tools.

Other tools targeting different platforms have also been identified such as an [Android implant](/intelligence/objects/malware--4c8a56d1-4bb9-4827-ad2d-faa402cdefa4) spread to Ukrainian gunners on the Donbass Front as well as IOS and OSX versions of the X-AGENT implant.

The operations of the APT28 intrusion set were closely linked to the operations of another threat actor dubbed "[Sandworm](/intelligence/objects/intrusion-set--f29bd8cc-1cea-497c-ac3f-8d590b95c9d6)", "Blackenergy" or "Hades". This second intrusion set has been attributed to another GRU unit, the unit 74455. It seems that these two threat actors worked together during several operations, APT28 giving the lead to Sandworm on some destabilization campaigns (Ukrainian crisis, US and French presidential elections). 

The distinction between these two intrusion sets is most often done from the tools used, Sandworm preferring open source offensive tools such as [Empire](/intelligence/objects/malware--43650dc8-980b-4b5f-9646-476cccbae2f7) or [Metasploit](/intelligence/objects/tool--57f456d7-20b2-4609-859e-54d9238946f0) during its operations. Which is now harder to perform now since APT28 also switched to open source tools.

### Campaigns

APT28 has become famous for its destabilization campaigns during several crisis contexts since 2013. APT28 was customary in the creation of fake hacktivist groups to allow the spreading of stolen information (emails, documents) from its victims or the claim of successful attacks. APT28 is also known for modifying stolen documents before making them public to increase the impact of destabilization. Here is a non-exhaustive list of several false flags and hacktivist groups operated by APT28, sometimes with the support of the Sandworm intrusion set.

|  Avatar/FalseFalg/Operation  | Context |  Use |  Attribution confidence |
|----------|---------------|-------|----------|
| CyberBerkut | Ukrainian crisis | Sabotage, leaks | High | 
| YemeniCyberArmy | Yemeni crisis | Leaks | High | 
| SyrianCyberArmy | Syrian crisis | DDoS attacks | High | 
| CyberCaliphate | Russia-occident tensions | Sabotage, Leaks | High | 
| Fancy Bear | Olympic Games doping ban | Leaks | High | 
| DCLeaks | US presidential elections 2016 | Leaks | High | 
| GUCCIFER 2.0 | US presidential elections 2016 | Leaks | High | 
| MacronLeaks | FR presidential elections | Leaks | High (Sandworm) | 
| OlympicDestroyer/Lazarus | Olympic Games doping ban, Pyeongchang. | Sabotage | Medium (Sandworm) | 
| RANA Leaks | Undetermined | Leaks | Low (overlaps with APT28 infrastructure & TTPs) | 

In its latest operations, APT28 seems to have gradually abandoned the creation of hacktivist avatars - which may have been judged too discriminating and heavy to implement - to give documents directly to journalists, influencers, or on several forums.

Following some operational security mistakes carried out by its operators and lawsuits engaged by occidental countries, a public attribution was carried out against this intrusion set. The attribution led to the public designation of several operators working within Units 26165 and 74455.

Following these lawsuits, the historical APT28 intrusion set (using its own tools, a discriminant infrastructure and carrying out false flags) seems to have mutated or disappeared. No more articles mentioning new attack campaigns associated with APT28 have been published since 2019.

In 2021, CLUSTER25 reported the use of a backdoor dubbed "[Skinny Boy](/intelligence/objects/malware--fa9a8c0d-1193-4bc1-8290-5c3a0dcbcc43)" which had potential links with APT28. However, the analysis of the backdoor and the context (mainly the associated infrastructure) done by SEKOIA.IO could not link it with high confidence to an APT28 resurgence.

The temporary end of the APT28 and Sandworm intrusion sets seem to have coincided with the resurgence of another Russian-speaking threat actor on the stage: [NOBELIUM](/intelligence/objects/intrusion-set--7dbe6e76-c59f-4dec-a7cf-c2a7e0210d16)/APT29, linked to the [SVR](/intelligence/objects/threat-actor--de741e1a-061d-449f-a7d8-8d8aee0069b1). This resurgence of APT29 could indicate the Kremlin preference for other intelligence services to engage in cyber operations. This choice could be directly linked to the past errors of APT28 and Sandworm.

In 2022, Trellix attributed an attack to APT28 targeting Western Asia. Trellix found a new malware dubbed Graphite using Microsoft OneDrive as C2.

A report from Cluster25 researchers described a phishing technique used by fancybear since at least February 2022. The group uses a PowerShell Slide Show (.pps) document which execute a PowerShell code contained in its 'HyperLinks' metadata when the user opens it in presentation mode and move its mouse over it.

### New TTPs

Over the current **Russia-Ukraine war**, APT28 conducted **widespread phishing campaigns** to collect information to **provide political and military advantage**, and relied on opportunistic access through historical compromise to conduct **destructive cyber attacks**.

These recent attacks saw the emergence of new TTPs. APT28 today seems to prefer the use of disposable implants often developed in interpreted languages such as **Javascript**, **Powershell** or simple **bat scripts**, created specifically for each campaign. Their implants are not sophisticated at all and often linked to carrying out a single task such as creating a tunnel, recovering & exfiltrating passwords & co.

APT28 also seems to have switched from registered VPS and domains to **Mockbin services**, **TOR (for tunneling)** and **compromised network appliances** to create their operational infrastructure. This prevent easy correlation from a Threat Intelligence perspective.

objects.description:
Olympic Destroyer is a worm and a wiper developed and operated by the Sandworm threat actor during the 2018 Winter Olympics in Pyeongchang, South Korea. Olympic Destroyer embeds several modules encrypted in AES in its PE resources such as:

* Windows Account Password Stealer
* A Destroyer / Wiper
* Copy of PsExec
* Browser Password Stealer
* A Loader

Two main variants of Olympic Destroyer have been seen ITW. The first version is a flawed version which spreads a OD binary which hasn't been patched with the stolen credentials, therefore, the impact is limited. The second variant isnt flawed. It spread the patched versions of Olympic Destroyer containing stolen credentials, thus allowing better worming capabilities.

objects.description:
The **General Staff of the Armed Forces** of the Russian Federation (Glavnoye Razvedyvatelnoye Upravlenie) is a military intelligence service which aim is to provide intelligence to the Ministry of Defense, the military leadership and Russian armed forces as a whole. This institution has been **reformed in 2010** and presents now a new acronym, **GU**, but is **still widely known under the GRU acronym** that we use in this description. Unlike Russia's other security and intelligence agencies such as the FSB and the SVR, which report to the president of the Russian Federation, the **head of the GRU is subordinate to the Russian military command**, reporting to the Minister of Defense. The Main Directorate controls the military intelligence service and maintains its own Special Forces units known as Spetsnaz. Although its missions are supposed to focus on intelligence collection to support military decision-making, the **GRU is in fact Russia's largest foreign-intelligence agency** conducting covert operations to **support foreign policy objectives**. Since 2004, the GRU has **developed significant cyber capabilities**, mixing it with its historical experience in conducting **psychological and information operations** inherited from the Soviet propaganda era. Russian military doctrine now includes a **new view of warfare** where the line between peace and conflict is blurred. In order to exploit this situation, the GRU considers that non-violent tools are important, thus **cyber operations as an effective and cheap tool** to **undermine, subvert, and manipulate** an adversary. This doctrine is the reason why, among classic espionage purposes, cyber operations detected from **GRU subgroups show deception, manipulation and sabotage objectives** when the FSB and the SVR operations are more silent and covert spying-oriented cyber operations. In line with the Russian government goals, the GRU seeks to manipulate domestic audiences and **undermine faith in democratic systems of government**. For example, in the context of the 2016 US presidential election, the Democratic National Committee (DNC) has been targeted in order to leak information with the purpose of undermining candidate Clinton. A GRU's operation has been exposed targeting the 2017 French presidential election where operatives leaked information from Macrons EM! party. Instead of seeking a particular candidate (as it was assumed for Trump), **the goal for Russian information operations focuses more on causing chaos and weakening the domestic legitimacy** of an adversarys government.
![](https://app.sekoia.io/api/v2/inthreat/images/b9645ad13412fcb8701240fda9844c6ef9f99bdbebd8486d0555fb9b1b36c92f.png) ### GRU Cyber Units and APTs
* **Unit 26165** aka 85th Main Special Service Center Unit 26165 **operates the intrusion set [APT 28](/intelligence/objects/intrusion-set--40479e35-a7ca-4c05-998d-2cf21ab751cc)** (aka Fancy Bear aka Sofacy). Unit 26165 is a **SIGINT unit** that collects information for various customers, including other GRU units responsible for covert operations. The unit, which is also known as the GRU 85 Main Special Service Center, is located at 20 Komsomolskiy Prospekt, Moscow. Unit 26165 conducted the **operation to exfiltrate emails** associated with **Hillary Clinton**s presidential election campaign and the Democratic National Committee in 2016, **then gave it to Unit 74455 to organize the DCLeaks campaign** in parallel to the creation of Guccifer 2.0 avatar. The GRU officers arrested in the Netherlands while conducting a close access operation against the OPCW network were also from Unit 26165. * **Unit 74455** aka Main Center for Special Technologies (GTsST) Unit 74455 **operates the intrusion set [Sandworm](/intelligence/objects/intrusion-set--f29bd8cc-1cea-497c-ac3f-8d590b95c9d6)** (aka Telebots aka IRIDIUM). Unit 74455 appears to be a recent unit created to help support and expand the GRUs cyber operation and information warfare. Unit 74455, is also known as the Main Center for Special Technologies, and is commonly referred to by media reports and the U.S. government as Sandworm. Located in the Moscow suburbs, Unit 74455 is suspected to have built and manipulated the **Guccifer 2.0 avatar** used to leak information from the **2016 DNC hack**. This unit is **specialized into hybrid, destructive and destabilization operations** such as the MacronLeaks, the 2017 NotPetya attack or the Industroyer campaigns against the Ukrainian power grid. * **Unit 54777** aka 72nd Special Service Center The Special Service Center is reportedly responsible for the **GRUs psychological operations** that maintain front organizations, including **InfoRos** and the Institute of the Russian Diaspora. InfoRos was named in the 2021 US sanctions as an **organization that spreads false conspiracy narratives** and disinformation promoted by GRU officials (COVID-19 spreading through OTAN soldiers disinformation campaigns). According to open-source publications, GRUs InfoRos has registered about 1,300 online news websites including in the domestic web (attached to cities, towns, districts, or even villages) in order to amplify that broadcast the Russian governments narrative. **There is no known intrusion set linked to this unit**. * **Unknown GRU unit** Not enough technical clues or open-sources publications attribute **the intrusion set [Ember Bear](/intelligence/objects/intrusion-set--545e1e88-42d7-43ec-816e-0702bef0dacd)** (aka Lorec53 aka UAC-0056) to a specific GRU unit. Howerver, according to Crowdstrike, **Ember Bear TTPs are consistent with other GRU cyber operations**. This group has operated against government and military organizations in Eastern Europe since early 2021, likely to **collect intelligence** from target networks. Crowdstrike attributes the WhisperGate sabotage campaign to Ember Bear with moderate confidence. On January 31, 2022, CERT-UA publicly attributed to Ember Bear an attack targeting an energy organization in Ukraine. * The **Central Scientific Institute of Chemistry and Mechanics** This institution, which is a research organization part of the Russian Ministry of Defence, but is not under direct GRU administration, **operates the intrustion set [XENOTIME](/intelligence/objects/intrusion-set--7b3fddaf-ee4d-4009-bd04-fccfdbeeee43)** (aka TEMP.Veles aka Triton). XENOTIME operators associated with the Institute have **developed destructive ICS malware** known as **Triton** (also called HatMan and TRISIS) which has been exposed and sanctioned by the U.S. Department of the Treasury and by the UK Foreign, Commonwealth, and Development Office (FCDO) for a 2017 incident that involved safety override controls in a foreign oil refinery. ### GRUs most exposed cyber operations (not exclusive)
* **CyberBerkut ([APT 28](/intelligence/objects/intrusion-set--40479e35-a7ca-4c05-998d-2cf21ab751cc))** During the 2014 Ukrainian presidential election, a series of malicious activities against Kyiv electoral institutions - including destructive operations, data leak and DDoS attack, where performed under the CyberBerkut avatar, in an attempt to undermine and/or influence election resultats. * **TV5 Monde (APT28)** A 2015 false flag destructive cyberattack that shut down every broadcast channel of the French international TV network while diffusing fake Islamic State propaganda. The attack was conducted by APT28 in retaliation from the French position on the 2014 Crimean Invasion and for the delivery cancellation of two French Mistral-class helicopter carriers ordered in 2010 by Russia. * **Ukraine power grid hack ([Sandworm](/intelligence/objects/intrusion-set--f29bd8cc-1cea-497c-ac3f-8d590b95c9d6))** December 2015 destructive attacks on Ukraines electrical infrastructure, Ministry of Finance, and State Treasury Service. * **DCLeaks (APT28 and Sandworm)** During the 2016 US presidential election, APT28 and Sandworm targeted DNCs email network (among other targets such as voting machines), and dumped emails from Democratic Party leaders. The leak was orchestrated with the creation of Guccifer 2.0 and DCLeaks websites in order to mess with the election and undermine US institutions. * **MacronLeaks (APT28 and Sandworm)** 2017 hack-and-leak operation targeting French President Emmanuel Macrons emails and interference in Frances presidential election. * **[NotPetya](/intelligence/objects/campaign--595f55b5-0e99-412b-9a0c-5a5cecd9cd2d) ransomware (Sandworm)** 2017 ransomware attack initially targeting Ukraine but which infected computers globally and caused an estimated $10 billion in damage. * **[Olympic Destroyer](/intelligence/objects/campaign--c7bb8f6b-0092-49a7-8b88-d356c0ef61ff) (Sandworm)** 2018 false flag destructive cyber operation against the PyeongChang Winter Olympics in South Korea. Operators tried to disguise themselves as North Korean operatives by using known TTPs attributed to the Lazarus intrusion set. * **OPCW close access operation (Sandworm)** In 2018, in a global cyber offensive campaign against UK and European institutions, GRU officers have been arrested in the Netherlands trying to access the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons investigating the nerve agent attack against Sergei Skripal.

objects.description:
**Mimikatz** is an open-source post-exploitation framework created in 2008 by security researcher Benjamin Delpy as a proof of concept to show vulnerabilities on how Microsoft Windows handles authentication credentials.

Mimikatz has many functionalities, and is **widely used by Intrusion Sets (cybercriminal and State-nexus) to steal credentials** - extract plaintext passwords from memory, password hashes, PIN codes and cryptographic attributes **to forge Kerberos tickets**.

Although originally written in C, as its source code is available publicly, many people refactored it in other languages such as .NET, Python and Powershell to avoid detection or facilitate the integration of part of its modules in other tools.

objects.description:
Meterpreter is an advanced, dynamically extensible payload that uses in-memory DLL injection stagers and is extended over the network at runtime. It communicates over the stager socket and provides a comprehensive client-side Ruby API. It features command history, tab completion, channels, and more.

Metepreter was originally written by skape for Metasploit 2.x, common extensions were merged for 3.x and is currently undergoing an overhaul for Metasploit 3.3

**How Meterpreter Works**
* The target executes the initial stager. This is usually one of bind, reverse, findtag, passivex, etc.
* The stager loads the DLL prefixed with Reflective. The Reflective stub handles the loading/injection of the DLL.
* The Metepreter core initializes, establishes a TLS/1.0 link over the socket and sends a GET. Metasploit receives this GET and configures the client.
* Lastly, Meterpreter loads extensions. It will always load stdapi and will load priv if the module gives administrative rights. All of these extensions are loaded over TLS/1.0 using a TLV protocol.

 
**Meterpreter Design Goals**
* Meterpreter resides entirely in memory and writes nothing to disk.
* No new processes are created as Meterpreter injects itself into the compromised process and can migrate to other running processes easily.
* By default, Meterpreter uses encrypted communications.
* All of these provide limited forensic evidence and impact on the victim machine.

objects.description:
PsExec is a light-weight telnet-replacement that lets you execute processes on other systems, complete with full interactivity for console applications, without having to manually install client software. PsExec's most powerful uses include launching interactive command-prompts on remote systems and remote-enabling tools like IpConfig that otherwise do not have the ability to show information about remote systems.

**Even if PSExec is a legitimate executable signed by Microsoft, this tool is used by a bunch of attackers and ransomware operators for their lateral movement/ransomware spreading. If you don't use PSExec during your daily administration tasks (which is not recommended) and you have detected abnormal PSExec execution in your environment, please investigate.**

[Olympic Destroyer](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0365) overwrites files locally and on remote shares.(Citation: Talos Olympic Destroyer 2018)(Citation: US District Court Indictment GRU Unit 74455 October 2020)

[Olympic Destroyer](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0365) uses the native Windows utilities vssadmin, wbadmin, and bcdedit to delete and disable operating system recovery features such as the Windows backup catalog and Windows Automatic Repair.(Citation: Talos Olympic Destroyer 2018)

[Olympic Destroyer](https://attack.mitre.org/software/S0365) will shut down the compromised system after it is done modifying system configuration settings.(Citation: Talos Olympic Destroyer 2018)(Citation: US District Court Indictment GRU Unit 74455 October 2020)
